The TOAR vegetation exposure metric that is focused on the mid-range of hourly average levels is: 
 
  

The daily 12-h (0800–1959h) average exposure metric (M12) (in units of ppb) was widely used in the past to characterize crop exposures to establish crop-specific exposure–response relationships, which relate a quantifiable mean to a reduction in crop yield (
    Heck et al., 1988; 
    Jäger et al., 1992; 
    Legge et al., 1995). In post-experimental data analysis, cumulative metrics, such as the SUM06 (the accumulation of all hourly average values equal to and above 0.06 ppm) and W126 indices (
    US EPA, 2013; 
    US Federal Register, 2015) better fit the yield loss observations for experiments conducted in the US, and thus have received greater focus than average metrics (
    Tingey et al., 1991; 
    Lefohn and Foley, 1993; 
    Mauzerall and Wang, 2001). 
    Supplemental Material provides additional information on the 12-h exposure metric. In the TOAR program, the M12 exposure index is specified over the following time periods: (a) M12 (3-month, 12-h for wheat and rice), (b) M12 (6-month
    , 12-h), (c) M12 (7-month, 12-h), and (d) M12 (12-month, 12-h for tropical or subtropical moist climate zones) (0800–1959h).
